    <item>
      <title>2024-07-03</title>
      <link>/wily/2024/jul-2024/20240703/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>/wily/2024/jul-2024/20240703/</guid>
      <description>
        
        
        &lt;h2&gt;Vim Learnings&lt;span class=&#34;absolute -mt-20&#34; id=&#34;vim-learnings&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;a href=&#34;#vim-learnings&#34; class=&#34;subheading-anchor&#34; aria-label=&#34;Permalink for this section&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Keybindings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Put command:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;p&lt;/code&gt;: put/paste the deleted text, after the text cursor&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Replace Command:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;r&amp;lt;character&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;: replace command, for example the word &lt;code&gt;typod&lt;/code&gt; where &lt;code&gt;o&lt;/code&gt; has to be replaced with &lt;code&gt;e&lt;/code&gt; to make it &lt;code&gt;typed&lt;/code&gt;, move the cursor to the start of the character to be placed(until o) and type &lt;code&gt;re&lt;/code&gt; to replace &lt;code&gt;o&lt;/code&gt; with &lt;code&gt;e&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Change Command: delete all the characters from the cursor till the end of the word.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;ce&lt;/code&gt;: &lt;code&gt;VNKLO&lt;/code&gt;, move the cursor to the right of&lt;code&gt;V&lt;/code&gt; and input &lt;code&gt;ce&lt;/code&gt;,which deletes all the characters till the end, and type in the required characters.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Internet Protocol&lt;span class=&#34;absolute -mt-20&#34; id=&#34;internet-protocol&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;a href=&#34;#internet-protocol&#34; class=&#34;subheading-anchor&#34; aria-label=&#34;Permalink for this section&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;IPV4&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;32bit integers,represented in 4 numbers separated by &lt;code&gt;.&lt;/code&gt; and the numbers are ranging from 0-255.
&lt;code&gt;192.168.1.1&lt;/code&gt;: example of IPV4 address.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Drawbacks:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Limited Address space&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Complex configuration: IPv4 requires mannual configuration or DHCP to assign address.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Fragmentation: IPv4 allows to fragment packets,chances of packets getting lost.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;IPV6&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To support increased use of computer networks, internet enabled devices, ipv6 was invented.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Enhanced packet header for efficient routing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Data security through IPSec header field.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ipv6 address representation as &lt;code&gt;x:x:x:x:x:x:x:x&lt;/code&gt;,where x is the hexadecimal values of eight 16digit pieces.
Ipv6 addresses ranges from:
&lt;code&gt;0000:0000:0000:0000:0000:0000:0000:0000&lt;/code&gt; to &lt;code&gt;ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Shorthand formats of IPV6 addresses.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Omit leading zeros
Specify IPv6 addresses by omitting leading zeros. For example, IPv6 address 1050:0000:0000:0000:0005:0600:300c:326b can be written as 1050:0:0:0:5:600:300c:326b.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Double colon
Specify IPv6 addresses by using double colons (::) in place of a series of zeros. For example, IPv6 address ff06:0:0:0:0:0:0:c3 can be written as ff06::c3. Double colons can be used only once in an IP address.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

      </description>
    </item>
    
